default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPull - 
defaultFoster R&amp;D via financial rewards, e.g. monetary prizes for delivering specific results
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPush - Reducing the cost of R&amp;D
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLego-regulatory - similar to pull mechanisms, but use the market to determine reward size
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHybrid - a mixture of pull/push mechanisms
default&#xa0;
defaultThe proposals of The Consultative Expert Working Group on R&amp;D: Financing and Coordination (CEWG) (WHO, 2012) report are discussed below, including the pull mechanisms and cross-border initiatives endorsed by the report authors 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe CEWG was commissioned by the World Health Assembly in 2010 to look into methods to stimulate R&amp;D financing and coordination in sectors failed my traditional market forces. The CEWG report evaluated several proposals for reform in R&amp;D structures including tax breaks for companies and orphan drug legislation. Criticisms of these approaches are touched upon in other sections of this report. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultObjectives
defaultThis proposal, endorsed by the CEWG report, sought negotiations under the WHO for a new treaty between member states for Health R&amp;D. As stated in the CEWG report the treaty seeks to promote “a sustainable model of medical innovation”. 
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo address this goal the elements of a proposed treaty would include the following:
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCoordination mechanisms - development of appropriate R&amp;D networks to facilitate the efficient transfer of knowledge
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFinancing - ensuring a predictable funding source, mainly from a defined contribution from different governments. Criteria for financing should incorporate:
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultR&amp;D incentives that further the de-linking of R&amp;D costs from the costs of the final products
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultR&amp;D targeted at specific global health priority products such as antibiotics as well as the special health needs of currently neglected developing countries
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultManagement of R&amp;D outcomes, assets and intellectual property rights - ensuring the open sharing of knowledge and the products of R&amp;D to protect the public interest and encourage further innovation potential.
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo produce sustainable financing for R&amp;D under the treaty, it is proposed that WHO member state governments contribute a fixed proportion of GDP. 
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe amount specified would be determined based on a country’s level of development and managed under a transparent system. 
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSupplementary financing from other sources would also be considered under the treaty. 
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo generate their respective contributions it is proposed member states use mandatory levies on certain products or other tax-based systems,
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExamples cited including a financial transactions tax and smoking taxation. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo guide and supervise the funding of R&amp;D proposals under the auspices of the treaty an R&amp;D architecture would be designed to guide priority setting and perform a research needs assessment.
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe components of a proposed global R&amp;D architecture are:
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNeeds assessment - identify specific health problems at each population level and existing healthcare resources available in each needs domain. 
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPriority setting - areas of greatest need or in areas where current R&amp;D activity is low or non-existent prioritised with funding.
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultR&amp;D funding structure - determine the specific incentives used to fund R&amp;D. 
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDelinking is the main approach the treaty promotes with incentives
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe treaty is flexible in incentives used to fund R&amp;D, certain projects may benefit from targeted prize funds or grants whilst others may be better developed by socially responsible licensing policies. 
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOther guiding principles in addition to delinking include
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFunding should be provided for all aspects of R&amp;D, including the relevant clinical trials needed for formal market authorisation.
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIntellectual property management - treaty funded R&amp;D research outcomes should not be monopolized by IP patent protections. This is to encourage maximum further innovation efforts from each R&amp;D product. 
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMonitoring - a key principle is the development of coordinated R&amp;D efforts at each level of government and research. 
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK government should take steps to promote the adoption of the Global R&amp;D treaty under the WHO as part of its AMR strategy. The treaty addresses the structural problems that currently restrict the drug development pipeline including:
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMarket failure - the current patent driven innovation system, as discussed in the introduction, fails to encourage R&amp;D into antibiotic agents
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCo-ordination - the Global R&amp;D treaty enshrines coordinated research approaches as one of the core principles in its recommendations. Other aspects of the treaty help foster coordinated R&amp;D approaches:
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIntellectual property management - R&amp;D funded under the treaty will not be monopolised using patent incentives, this eases further research into newly developed therapeutic agents by follow-on research.
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMonitoring systems - the treaty encourages review of R&amp;D funded projects 
default(3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNeeds assessment and Priority-setting - by identifying key areas for research based on population level health needs the treaty encourages a focus on international health priorities such as AMR. 
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAffordability - The current paradigm drug development leads to expensive therapies being brought to market. Newer antibiotics will be widely used and pose significant financial burdens on existing healthcare systems. Adopting the Global R&amp;D treaty will reduce the costs of antibiotics developed by R&amp;D funded by the treaty.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDiscussions promoting adoption of a global R&amp;D treaty have been ongoing for 14 years now with significant input from both governmental, private-sector and civil society actors (Kidell-Monroe and Helene Iversen et al., 2013). 
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAn open-ended WHO meeting convened on November 2012 to follow up on the CEWG report recommendations drafted a resolution for the World Health Assembly to postpone discussion on the main report recommendations, specifically the R&amp;D treaty, until 2016. (Love, 2013)
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWith debate postponed till 2016 it is imperative that the UK government reconsiders its position on the CEWG report in concordance with principles of Human Rights and in face of the previously acknowledged urgent and unaddressed problems in health both local and global. 
