default&#xa0;
defaultDirect funding of grants/fellowships &amp; Translational research
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe NIHR put together an AMR themed call as a result of the Chief Medical Officers 2011 Annual Report
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt’s seen eight NIHR funding programmes put out calls for funding applications into research to collect data and develop solutions for key areas 1-3 in the governments AMR strategy. (NIHR 2013)
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever to tackle key area 4 would require the government to provide a major increase in direct funding of antibiotic research through the MRC to the UKCRC Translational Infection Research Initiative.
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK already offers one of the most generous R&amp;D tax credit systems in the world
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default175% (under the SME scheme) or 130% (under the large company scheme) of qualifying expenditure on R&amp;D activities is deducted when calculating their profit for tax purposes (HMRC) cf. 13.5% in Belgium (WHO, 2010) 
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultProviding tax credits to private sector companies can be a double edged sword in stimulating R&amp;D funding. 
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe criteria to qualify for the current tax credits require companies to be performing any R&amp;D with an aim to ‘advance science and technology’.
defaulte)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis blanket use of tax credits has seen the cost to government increase from £89 million in 2000-2001 to £1.1 billion in 2010-2011, with the majority going to large companies.
defaultf)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDespite this the number of innovative medicines coming to the market has been falling
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPharmaceutical companies increasingly put their focus on developing ‘me-too’ drugs that offer little to no clinical benefit
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultrather than the tax credits stimulating innovation they often simply boosting the profits of companies engaging in the R&amp;D.
defaultg)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn order to stimulate innovation tax credits need to be directed at areas of R&amp;D where the market is failing, ie. AMR, and their ability to make an appreciable improvement to an existing product needs to be more thoroughly proven. 
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA type of public-private partnership, the PDP is a virtual non-profit organisation which outsources activities to partners in the academic, NGO, public and private sectors, using funding and other contributions from public and in-kind private sources (Grace, 2010).
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMultiple avenues of innovation are pursued simultaneously, with a portfolio of pharmaceutical R&amp;D projects managed by the PDP and consulted on by an independent committee of scientific experts.
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTheir main functions, then, are the following:
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLink expertise from different spheres;
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultProvide public funding;
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultProvide technical oversight;
defaultiv)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultManage a portfolio of research projects.
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThey operate with the objective of developing health products of a specific type (e.g. drugs or vaccines) and, in some cases, for a specific disease area.
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis is a novel partnership model proposed by Rudolph Juliano (2013), in order to adapt the PDP model so that its benefits may be applied to R&amp;D outside of NTDs.
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe model he describes is as follows.
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPartners from the academic, NGO and biopharmaceutical sectors form a joint venture virtual organisation (a ‘Board of Directors’, as shown in Figure 1), responsible for the management of a portfolio of research projects (in the same vein as PDPs), which may be outsourced to contract research organisations (CROs). CROs may also be partners.
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA governmental funding body sets the research agenda (according to public health need), and invites applications for grant funding from different, competing NPDDCs.
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultApplications will contain meticulous details as to the contributions of and division of labour between different partners, the share ownership and intellectual property arrangements concerning the resultant technology, as well as conventional research proposals concerning the line of inquiry to be pursued.
defaultiv)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultContributions of partners need not necessarily be financial. Pharmaceutical companies, for example, could donate access to chemical databases or human resources on a 
defaultpro bono
default basis, while universities could offer faculty research time (Juliano, 2013).
defaultv)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGrant funding will be allocated on the strength of these applications.
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMultiple NPDDCs may be recruited by government to pursue the same, or different, research goals in parallel.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe amount of new molecular entities developed per $billion spend on R&amp;D has declined during the last half decade. This is speculated to be for numerous reasons, one being an increase in regulatory costs
default&#xa0;
defaultThree lego-regulatory mechanisms are mentioned in the CMO’s report
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExpediting regulatory review
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExtending patent terms
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAdjusting pricing or reimbursement procedures
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA review of the current evidence of these three mechanisms shows that they have little potential for significant impact when addressing the market failures involved in development of novel antibiotics.
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMarket-based interventions will only have success were the market is an appropriate mechanism for delivery, where the incentives of the market match the needs of society.
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCurrently, pharmaceuticals are expensive because the price is linked to all preceding expenditure; are of consistently poor quality; and are not developed according to needs based priorities. 
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConsidering the fact that pharmaceutical companies enter less profitable markets for strategic, rather than commercial concerns, brings into questions the efficacy of lego-regulatory mechanisms. (Moran, 2005)
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPatents increase innovation only as measured by the number of patents issues. The effect of more stringent intellectual property laws has seen a dramatic increase in the number of patents issued. (Abrams, 2009)
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhile patents and patent terms have increased, the number of effective new drugs being developed (a far better measure of innovation) has not increased. Of 961 new drugs licensed from 1999-2008 only 2% of these were found to give a significant therapeutic advantage.(Anon, 2012) 
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSpecifically to antibiotics, while TRIPS has set 20 year patents as a global norm the number of new antibiotics has actually halved between the periods 1983-87 (16 antibiotics) and 1998-2002 (7 antibiotics) (Spellberg et al., 2004)
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPatent term extensions have been trialled in orphan drug legislation
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMore stringent criteria are required to assess Orphan medicinal product’s efficacy and cost/effectiveness to improve the clinical value and the affordability of products allowed onto the market (Joppi et al, 2013)
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBurdensome regulatory processes may disincentivise otherwise willing pharmaceutical companies from developing drugs for small markets. 
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultReducing the regulatory requirements may reduce the cost of entering the market. 
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, minimum regulatory requirements must be met to secure efficacious new developments. 
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultReducing the regulatory requirements results in more unsafe drugs being approved (Olson, 2008) 
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNew regulatory measures should continue to be analysed
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe use of non-inferiority in clinical trials is a subject of fierce debate 
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultProving safety and efficacy should be the fundamental goal 
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn cases where no effective treatment exists it could be argued a relatively toxic treatment may be better than nothing.
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAdjusting the price government pays for branded antibiotics would increase potential revenues thereby incentivising R&amp;D
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPricing procedures could bring an added benefit when they are linked in some way to the therapeutic or social value of the drug. 
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSuch an approach would be technically complex and expensive
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the UK, the government are moving from the Pharmaceutical Price Referencing System (PPRS) to Value-Based Pricing 
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPPRS is a voluntary agreement between the Department of Health and the pharmaceutical industry
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnder this agreement the industry has the freedom to set the price, but the government can regulate the amount of profit allowed to make through sales to the NHS.
defaulte)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultValue-Based Pricing will involve setting the price according to certain cost-effectiveness measurements such as cost per Quality Adjusted Life Years gained.
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere will be proposed cost-effectiveness thresholds for any given drug.
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe government has proposed setting higher thresholds
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultfor drugs treating diseases with a higher burden of illness (particularly those with unmet need);
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultfor drugs that demonstrate an increase in therapeutic effectiveness;
default(3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultfor drugs that demonstrate a ‘wider societal benefit’ (Department of Health, 2010)
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPharmaceutical companies will be free to propose a price, which NICE will then assess for cost-effectiveness. If the price is found to exceed cost-effectiveness, companies will be asked to provide robust evidence to justify a higher price.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Global R&amp;D treaty, if adopted, would produce a huge impact on public health and allow governmental actors to help tailor research agendas to the specific health needs of their populations and pressing global health concerns such as antimicrobial resistance. Signing onto a legal framework will ensure sustainable R&amp;D funding allied to public health needs and also improve the wider availability of the products of research. 
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSupport the efforts of the WHO to develop a Global R&amp;D Treaty
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIncrease direct grant funding to the MRC UKCRC Translational Infection Research Initiative
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPut together a Non-profit Drug Development Corporation under the auspices of the Department of Business, Innovation &amp; Skills and the Department of Health to direct AMR research
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAdapt the R&amp;D tax credits system to promote true innovation and direct the research agenda
defaulte)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultReview medicines regulatory mechanisms, bearing in mind safety concerns
defaultf)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultClosely monitor the introduction of value based pricing of medicines with a view to ensuring cost effectiveness, transparency and its effect on stimulating R&amp;D
