default&#xa0;
defaultProposal
defaultAdvantages
defaultDisadvantages
defaultGlobal R&amp;D treaty
defaultDe-linking mechanism - the Global R&amp;D treaty offers an alternative financing approach that ‘de-links’ the cost of R&amp;D from the demands of profitability optimising the research agenda towards health need cf. economic need.
default&#xa0;
defaultCo-ordination - the Global R&amp;D treaty enshrines coordinated research approaches as one of the core principles.
default&#xa0;
defaultIntellectual property management - R&amp;D funded under the treaty will not be monopolised using patent incentives, this encourages innovation with follow-on research to further improve therapeutic efficacy of new medications developed. 
default&#xa0;
defaultNeeds assessment and Priority-setting - by identifying key areas for research based on population level health needs the treaty encourages a focus on international health priorities such as AMR. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAffordability - currently newly developed drug compounds are expensive when initially brought to market, adopting this approach will avoid this by facilitating at-cost pricing of newly developed therapeutic agents.
defaultThe Global R&amp;D treaty has not yet been implemented with further international support needed.
default&#xa0;
defaultDirect Funding / Grants
defaultGovernment directed research agenda
default&#xa0;
defaultFunds basic (pre-clinical) research, most neglected by industry
default&#xa0;
defaultAttractive to SMEs due to limited R&amp;D funding resources
defaultMRC is experienced in performing world class translational research 
defaultInformation asymmetry between funder and researcher - Research groups may have incentive to present research in the most positive light in order to maintain funding, and may lack motivation to continue development once push funding ends
default&#xa0;
defaultTax Credits (as used currently in UK)
defaultReduces R&amp;D costs to industry
defaultExpensive
default&#xa0;
defaultDoesn’t stimulate innovation
default&#xa0;
defaultDoesn’t allow government to direct research agenda
defaultProduct Development Partnerships
defaultHarness the inputs of diverse entities, allowing the optimal utilisation of their respective resources and unleashing otherwise untapped potential, including:
default&#xa0;
defaultUnprecedented up-scaling and commercialisation of novel academic discoveries using the capital and experience of private sector actors;
default&#xa0;
defaultNavigation of new and unfamiliar markets by private sector actors, with the aid of field-experienced NGOs;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe partnership model allows for the development of in-roads for the training of the next generation of human resources in pharmaceutical R&amp;D (Grace, 2010).
default&#xa0;
defaultVirtual administrative structure keeps overheads low (Munos, 2006).
defaultProject focus allows for rapid decision-making unfettered by conflicting business interests (Munos, 2006; Juliano, 2013).
default&#xa0;
defaultOutsourcing tasks to Contract Research Organisations (CROs) bypasses the need for out-of-pocket expenditure 
defaulton start-up capital, reducing costs (Hu et al, 2007).
default&#xa0;
defaultHistorically, PDPs have been able to operate on very small budgets compared with ‘big pharma’. For example, the cumulative spend by the Medicines for Malaria Venture between 2000 and 2005 was USD 100 million, 90% of which funded actual research (Munos, 2006).
default&#xa0;
defaultBuilds research capacity in developing countries (Juliano, 2013).
default&#xa0;
defaultSome PDPs offer private sector actors intellectual property over the results of their contributions in order to secure their input, with the opportunity of developing more commercial applications for new technologies (Pugatch et al, 2012). 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe model has so far failed to demonstrate its sustainability, with the majority of projects coming from shelved pharmaceutical company projects (Munos, 2006).
default&#xa0;
defaultContinued reliance on philanthropic funding is unsustainable (CEWG, 2012).
default&#xa0;
defaultThe PDP model has yet to be applied to an area other than neglected and tropical diseases (Munos, 2006).
default&#xa0;
defaultNon-profit Drug Development Corporations (NPDDCs)
defaultCorporate entities may be induced to join these partnerships with the prospect of different income streams in the form of government purchases, as well as royalties from licensing of products to manufacturers of generics.
default&#xa0;
defaultGovernment may set the research agenda, encouraging drug development to meet public health needs.
default&#xa0;
defaultFinancial reward for investment by government allows for the refilling of public coffers, contrasting with tax credits which constitute a one-way flow of public finances.
default&#xa0;
defaultNPDDC business model is in line with ethos of BIS’ Catapult initiative, in developing a deeper relationship between academia and industry.
defaultAcademic partners stand to make greater financial returns on the work that they contribute to commercially-viable 
defaultknowledge.
default&#xa0;
defaultFostering a deep relationship between academia and industry allows for the development of graduate career prospects.
defaultAs yet untested as a business model
defaultExtending Patent Terms
defaultMonopoly power offered to pharmaceutical companies offers a financial reward for developing new pharmaceuticals.
default&#xa0;
defaultPatent term extensions would be relatively easy to implement, because patenting systems are already in place.
defaultThe patent system is liable to abuse, because it provides 
default“an incentive to game the system by artificially creating monopolistic market conditions.”
default  (Simoens, 2011)
default&#xa0;
defaultThe patent system is not proven as a way of increasing development of innovative and clinically effective new medicines.
default&#xa0;
defaultReduces access to end product due to monopoly pricing. (Duerden, 2010)
default&#xa0;
defaultSignificant difficulties have been proposed when trying to apply patent term extensions to one class of drug only, without influencing other areas of R&amp;D. 
default(Kesselheim, 2010).
default&#xa0;
defaultA significant potential confounding factor in establishing the affordability of new pricing procedures is the current market share of generics in the UK. Specifically for ‘infections’ medicine, the market share of generics is over 90%. Current expenditure on ‘infections’ pharmaceuticals is £273 million; this will rise significantly as new patented medicines are introduced. (Hawe, 2013)
default&#xa0;
defaultExpedited Regulatory Review
defaultSpeeds up review process offering companies faster access to market
default&#xa0;
defaultReduces the cost of regulatory processes, making overall 
defaultR&amp;D cheaper.
defaultCan result in poorer quality/evidenced medicines. In particular applications a) do not always provide a comprehensive toxicity profile b) were inappropriately compared to placebo when better treatment was available c) used very small sample groups d) relied too much on surrogate end-points e) were of inadequate trial length f) were for pre-
defaultexisting drugs g) 
default&#xa0;
defaultwhen receiving conditional approval were not followed by appropriate review.
default (Joppi et al. 2010)
defaultIneffective at stimulating R&amp;D for orphan drugs (63 products in ten years), for the majority of the 7,000 rare or orphan diseases, effective treatments have not been developed
default. 
default(Joppi et al, 2010)
